@BeginModule
@NewPage
@Name      = Splittime
@Title     = Split time steps of a dataset
@Section   = File operations
@Class     = File operation
@Arguments = ifile oprefix
@Operators = splithour splitday splitmon splitseas splityear

@BeginDescription
This module splits time steps of a dataset to several files with names
formed from the field header information and @file{oprefix}.
@EndDescription
@EndModule


@BeginOperator_splithour
@Title     = Split hours

@BeginDescription
Splits a file into pieces, one for each different hour.
Appends two digits with the hour to @file{oprefix} to 
form the output file names.
@EndDescription
@EndOperator


@BeginOperator_splitday
@Title     = Split days

@BeginDescription
Splits a file into pieces, one for each different day.
Appends two digits with the day to @file{oprefix} to 
form the output file names.
@EndDescription
@EndOperator


@BeginOperator_splitmon
@Title     = Split months

@BeginDescription
Splits a file into pieces, one for each different month.
Appends two digits with the month to @file{oprefix} to 
form the output file names.
@EndDescription
@EndOperator


@BeginOperator_splitseas
@Title     = Split seasons

@BeginDescription
Splits a file into pieces, one for each different season.
Appends three characters with the season to @file{oprefix} to 
form the output file names.
@EndDescription
@EndOperator


@BeginOperator_splityear
@Title     = Split years

@BeginDescription
Splits a file into pieces, one for each different year.
Appends four digits with the year to @file{oprefix} to 
form the output file names.
@EndDescription
@EndOperator


@BeginExample
Assumed the input GRIB dataset has time steps from
january to december. To split each month with all
variables into one separat file use:
@BeginVerbatim
   cdo splitmon ifile mon
@EndVerbatim
Result of '{\tt dir mon*}':
@BeginVerbatim
   mon01.grb  mon02.grb  mon03.grb  mon04.grb  mon05.grb  mon06.grb
   mon07.grb  mon08.grb  mon09.grb  mon10.grb  mon11.grb  mon12.grb
@EndVerbatim
@EndExample
